 tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aManaging Migration in Italy and the United States shows how the development of gatekeeping in the United States and Italy laid the groundwork for immigration restriction worldwide at the turn of the twentieth century. The volume brings together European and American scholars, many for the first time, effectively crossing national and disciplinary boundaries. Using archives on both sides of the Atlantic, the authors explore the rise of immigration restriction and the attendant growth of the bureaucracy to regulate migration through the lens of migration studies, transnational history, and diplomatic and international history. The essays contribute to recent scholarship on the global repercussions of immigration restriction and the complex web of interactions created by limits on mobility. Managing Migration brings to light Italy’s important role in the establishment of international border controls promoted by the United States and expands the chronology of restriction from its origins to the present.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aEinreisebeschränkung. 4aEinwanderungspolitik. 4aGrenzkontrolle. 4aMigrationsgeschichte. 4aMobilität. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aImmigration restriction.  aborder control.  ahistory of immgration.  amigration policy.  amobility.1 aBonsaver, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun-Strumfels, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun-Strumfels, Lauren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChoate, Mark I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela